# ğŸš€ pyinit - Your All-in-One Python Project Manager

**pyinit** is a comprehensive command-line tool that streamlines and automates the entire lifecycle of your Python projects. From initialization to deployment, pyinit handles the tedious setup tasks so you can focus on writing exceptional code.

---

## âœ¨ What Makes pyinit Special?

- **ğŸ¯ Zero-Config Project Scaffolding**: Launch production-ready projects in seconds with professional templates (app, cli, flask, lib)
- **ğŸ“¦ Smart Dependency Management**: Add, lock, update, and visualize your project's dependencies effortlessly
- **ğŸ” Automated Code Quality**: Format, lint, and test your code with unified, simple commands
- **ğŸª Git Hooks Integration**: Enforce code quality standards automatically before every commit
- **ğŸ Virtual Environment Management**: Create and remove isolated Python environments with explicit control
- **ğŸ³ Deployment Ready**: Generate Dockerfiles, bump semantic versions, and clean your workspace instantly
- **ğŸ”¬ Intelligent Project Diagnostics**: Scan your project structure and configuration for issues with actionable suggestions

---

## ğŸ”§ Installation

Get pyinit up and running in 3 simple steps:

### 1ï¸âƒ£ Clone the Repository

```bash
git clone https://github.com/karimmohamed-ottf/pyinit.git
cd pyinit
```

### 2ï¸âƒ£ Install Project Templates

**âš ï¸ Critical Step**: pyinit requires templates to be installed in a system-wide location.

```bash
sudo cp -r templates /usr/share/pyinit/
```

> **ğŸ’¡ Why sudo?** Templates are copied to `/usr/share/pyinit/` (a system directory) to make them globally accessible, regardless of where you run the tool.

### 3ï¸âƒ£ Install the Tool

Install pyinit in editable mode so any source code changes take effect immediately:

```bash
sudo pip install -e .
```

> **ğŸ“ Note for Arch Linux Users**: You may need to add the `--break-system-packages` flag. **Important**: Always run commands with this flag as a non-root user.

**Verify Installation**:
```bash
pyinit --help
```

